<DOC><DOCNO> AP880912-0265 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-12-88 1932EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Manville     09-12 0266</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Manville,0276</SECOND><HEAD>Manville Reaches Accord With Insurance Company</HEAD><DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Manville Corp. has reached an agreement withAmerican Centennial Insurance Co. in another settlement overinsurance disputes stemming from damage claims filed by formerasbestos workers, Manville officials announced Monday.   Terms of the agreement provide for three payments by AmericanCentennial, of Wilmington, Del., totaling $3.4 million, and willcover all of Manville's claims against the insurer for policiescovering the periods from July 1, 1980 to July 1, 1981, and fromJuly 1982 to July 1983, Manville said in a news release.   The settlement is conditional upon final court orders approvingthe settlement and the Bankruptcy Court's order confirmingManville's plan of reorganization, the release said.   A fairness hearing on the settlement and on other recentlyannounced asbestos-related insurance settlements will be held onSept. 28 in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York City.   The settlement ultimately will go into the Asbestos PropertyDamage Trust established under Manville's reorganization plan.   Manville has now reached settlements providing for paymentstotaling nearly $845 million with numerous other insurers.   The Manville plan requires insurance funding of $615 million inpresent value to fund a trust for compensating asbestos diseasesufferers, the release said, with insurance proceeds in excess ofthe $615 million passing through to the Asbestos Property DamageTrust.   Manville filed for bankruptcy protection on Aug. 26, 1982, whenmore than 400 asbestos-related lawsuits were being filed agaisntthe company each month.   A proposed reorganization plan was confirmed by the bankruptcycourt in December 1986, but it cannot be consummated until allappeals are exhausted.</TEXT></DOC>